The Federal Government is set to launch the National Emergency Medical Service and Ambulance System to provide prompt and efficient emergency Medical Service to the citizens, this is being done to eliminate delays in access to healthcare services thus reducing the high mortality rate in Nigeria.  The Minister of Health, Dr Osagie Ehanire who made this known at a Media Parley On Reproductive, Maternal, Newborn, Child, Adolescent and Elderly Health Plus Nutrition in Abuja, said this emergency medical service could reduce mortality by 50 percent in the country.  According to the Minister, the health indices of vulnerable populations is poor, with a maternal mortality rate of 512 per 100,000 live births, modern contraceptive prevalence rate at 17% for all family planning methods, neonatal mortality rate is 39 per 1,000 live births, amongst other degenerating health statistics which needs to be urgently addressed.  The Minister further stressed the need to strengthen engagement with media institutions and improve strategic communication tools, in order to drive social and behaviour change.  Our Correspondent, Raliat Adenekan reports that the Emir of Shonga in Kwara State, (Dr.) Haliru Yahaya said there should be a collaboration between health policymakers, traditional rulers and the media to address the numerous misconceptions about health issues in the communities.